{"parse":{"title":"The Fountain of Indolence","pageid":41820598,"revid":831321942,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p class=\"mw-empty-elt\">\n\n</p>\n<table class=\"infobox vevent\" style=\"width:22em;width: 22em; line-height: 1.4em; text-align: left; float:right;\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" class=\"summary\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;font-size: 125%; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic\">The Fountain of Indolence</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Fountain_of_Indolence_by_J._M._W._Turner.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Fountain of Indolence by J. M. W. Turner.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/14/Fountain_of_Indolence_by_J._M._W._Turner.jpg/300px-Fountain_of_Indolence_by_J._M._W._Turner.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"190\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/14/Fountain_of_Indolence_by_J._M._W._Turner.jpg/450px-Fountain_of_Indolence_by_J._M._W._Turner.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/14/Fountain_of_Indolence_by_J._M._W._Turner.jpg/600px-Fountain_of_Indolence_by_J._M._W._Turner.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1200\" data-file-height=\"760\" /></a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Artist</th><td class=\"attendee\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/J._M._W._Turner\" title=\"J. M. W. Turner\">J. M. W. Turner</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Year</th><td>\n1834</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Medium</th><td class=\"category\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/Oil_painting\" title=\"Oil painting\">Oil on canvas</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Dimensions</th><td>\n106.5&#160;cm&#32;\u00d7&#160;166.4&#160;cm&#32;(41.9&#160;in&#32;\u00d7&#160;65.5&#160;in)</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Location</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Beaverbrook_Art_Gallery\" title=\"Beaverbrook Art Gallery\">Beaverbrook Art Gallery</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Fredericton\" title=\"Fredericton\">Fredericton</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Accession</th><td>\n1959.259</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><i><b>The Fountain of Indolence</b></i> is an <a href=\"/wiki/Oil_painting\" title=\"Oil painting\">oil painting</a> by the English artist <a href=\"/wiki/J._M._W._Turner\" title=\"J. M. W. Turner\">J. M. W. Turner</a>. First exhibited in 1834, it is now in the collection of the <a href=\"/wiki/Beaverbrook_Art_Gallery\" title=\"Beaverbrook Art Gallery\">Beaverbrook Art Gallery</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Fredericton\" title=\"Fredericton\">Fredericton</a>, New Brunswick, Canada.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Subject\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Subject</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#The_Fountain_of_Fallacy\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\"><i>The Fountain of Fallacy</i></span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Subject\">Subject</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Fountain_of_Indolence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Subject\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The painting depicts a scene described in Canto 1 of <a href=\"/wiki/James_Thomson_(poet)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"James Thomson (poet)\">James Thomson</a>'s 1748 poem <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Castle_of_Indolence\" title=\"The Castle of Indolence\">The Castle of Indolence</a></i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Mitchell_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Mitchell-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> \n</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Thus easy-rob'd, they to the fountain sped<br />\nThat in the middle of the court up-threw<br />\nA stream, high spouting from its liquid bed,<br />\nAnd falling back again in drizzly dew;<br />\nThere each deep draughts, as deep he thirsted drew;<br />\nIt was a fountain of <a href=\"/wiki/Nepenthe\" title=\"Nepenthe\">nepenthe</a> rare;<br />\nWhence, as Dan Homer sings, huge pleasaunce grew,<br />\nAnd sweet oblivion of vile earthly care;<br />\nFair gladsome waking thoughts, and joyous dreams more fair.<sup id=\"cite_ref-RPO_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-RPO-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> \n</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It shows an imaginary landscape with <a href=\"/wiki/Classical_architecture\" title=\"Classical architecture\">Classical</a> buildings and ruins centred on the fountain, around and within which human and winged <a href=\"/wiki/Cupid\" title=\"Cupid\">Cupid</a>-like figures are grouped.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Fountain_of_Indolence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><i>The Fountain of Indolence</i> was first exhibited at the 66th <a href=\"/wiki/Royal_Academy_of_Arts\" title=\"Royal Academy of Arts\">Royal Academy</a> Exhibition at <a href=\"/wiki/Somerset_House\" title=\"Somerset House\">Somerset House</a> in May 1834, to a generally favourable reception.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Butlin_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Butlin-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Arnold_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Arnold-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> The subsequent history of the painting is unknown until 1882, when it was sold to <a href=\"/wiki/Thomas_Agnew_%26_Sons\" title=\"Thomas Agnew &amp; Sons\">Thomas Agnew &amp; Sons</a> by H. Lumley. <a href=\"/wiki/William_Henry_Vanderbilt\" title=\"William Henry Vanderbilt\">William Henry Vanderbilt</a> then purchased it from Agnew and it remained in the Vanderbilt family until 1958. <a href=\"/wiki/George_W._Vanderbilt\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"George W. Vanderbilt\">George W. Vanderbilt</a> loaned it to the <a href=\"/wiki/Metropolitan_Museum_of_Art\" title=\"Metropolitan Museum of Art\">Metropolitan Museum of Art</a> for an exhibition of British paintings in 1907.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Zalewski_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Zalewski-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In 1958 <a href=\"/wiki/Max_Aitken,_Lord_Beaverbrook\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Max Aitken, Lord Beaverbrook\">Lord Beaverbrook</a> was actively seeking a \"first-rate\" Turner painting for the Beaverbrook Art Gallery, which was to open the following year in Fredericton. He purchased <i>The Fountain of Indolence</i> from the dealers Leggatt Brothers of London.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Poitras_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Poitras-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup class=\"reference\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">:<span>87</span></sup> The painting became central to a dispute that developed in 2004 between the Gallery and the Beaverbrook UK Foundation, which claimed ownership of 133 paintings that had been acquired by Lord Beaverbrook for the Gallery. The Foundation proposed to take back and sell <i>The Fountain of Indolence</i>, which <a href=\"/wiki/Sotheby%27s\" title=\"Sotheby&#39;s\">Sotheby's</a> had valued in 2002 at between $16.7 and $25&#160;million in Canadian funds.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Poitras_6-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Poitras-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> <sup class=\"reference\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">:<span>203</span></sup>The Gallery denied that the Foundation owned the paintings, maintaining that they all belonged to the Gallery. Both sides agreed to submit to <a href=\"/wiki/Arbitration\" title=\"Arbitration\">arbitration</a>, which resulted in a 2007 ruling that 85 of the paintings, including <i>The Fountain of Indolence</i>, belonged to the Gallery, while the remaining 48 belonged to the Foundation. The Foundation appealed the ruling, but it was confirmed by an appeal panel in 2009.<sup id=\"cite_ref-CBC_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CBC-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"The_Fountain_of_Fallacy\"><i>The Fountain of Fallacy</i></span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Fountain_of_Indolence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: The Fountain of Fallacy\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The gap in the <a href=\"/wiki/Provenance\" title=\"Provenance\">provenance</a> of <i>The Fountain of Indolence</i> between 1834 and 1882 lends credence to the theory that it is identical with <i>The Fountain of Fallacy</i>, a painting which Turner exhibited at the <a href=\"/wiki/British_Institution\" title=\"British Institution\">British Institution</a> in 1839, accompanied by four lines from his own poem entitled <i>Fallacies of Hope</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Wildman_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Wildman-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> \n</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Its Rainbow-dew diffused fell on each anxious lip,<br />\nWorking wild fantasy, imagining;<br />\nFirst, Science in the immeasurable Abyss of thought,<br />\nMeasured her orbit slumbering. \n</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Contemporary descriptions of the <i>Fountain of Fallacy</i> apply equally well to <i>The Fountain of Indolence</i>. In 1839, the year it was exhibited, Turner wrote to a Mr. Marshall that <i>The Fountain of Fallacy</i> was for sale for 400 guineas and that he had no other painting of that size for sale. No subsequent ownership history of <i>The Fountain of Fallacy</i> is known and the only recorded references to it after its first exhibition are two comments by <a href=\"/wiki/John_Ruskin\" title=\"John Ruskin\">John Ruskin</a>. According to Turner expert <a href=\"/wiki/Martin_Butlin\" title=\"Martin Butlin\">Martin Butlin</a>, in the <a href=\"/wiki/Catalogue_raisonn%C3%A9\" title=\"Catalogue raisonn\u00e9\">catalogue raisonn\u00e9</a> <i>The Paintings of J.M.W. Turner</i>, the available evidence indicates \"that in fact there was \u2013 and is \u2013 only one\" picture.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Butlin2_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Butlin2-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=The_Fountain_of_Indolence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Mitchell-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Mitchell_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Mitchell, Sebastian (2011). \"James Thomson's picture collection and British history painting\". <i>Journal of the History of Collections</i>. <b>23</b> (1): 127\u2013151. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1093/jhc/fhq017\">10.1093/jhc/fhq017</a>. <q>Turner was the most prominent of many nineteenth-century painters to admire Thomson's verse.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+the+History+of+Collections&amp;rft.atitle=James+Thomson%27s+picture+collection+and+British+history+painting&amp;rft.volume=23&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.pages=127-151&amp;rft.date=2011&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1093%2Fjhc%2Ffhq017&amp;rft.aulast=Mitchell&amp;rft.aufirst=Sebastian&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThe+Fountain+of+Indolence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-RPO-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-RPO_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Thomson, James. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://rpo.library.utoronto.ca/poems/castle-indolence-canto-i\">\"The Castle of Indolence Canto 1\"</a>. <i>RPO: Representative poetry online</i>. University of Toronto Libraries<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2 February</span> 2014</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=RPO%3A+Representative+poetry+online&amp;rft.atitle=The+Castle+of+Indolence+Canto+1&amp;rft.aulast=Thomson&amp;rft.aufirst=James&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Frpo.library.utoronto.ca%2Fpoems%2Fcastle-indolence-canto-i&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThe+Fountain+of+Indolence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Butlin-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Butlin_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Butlin, Martin; Joll, Evelyn (1977). <i>The Paintings of J.M.W. Turner</i>. New Haven: Yale University Press. pp.&#160;185\u2013186. <q>The critics recognized that it was a work of imagination and thus were willing to allow Turner more license than normal in the use of colours.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Paintings+of+J.M.W.+Turner&amp;rft.place=New+Haven&amp;rft.pages=185-186&amp;rft.pub=Yale+University+Press&amp;rft.date=1977&amp;rft.aulast=Butlin&amp;rft.aufirst=Martin&amp;rft.au=Joll%2C+Evelyn&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThe+Fountain+of+Indolence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Arnold-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Arnold_4-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=Gl0oAAAAYAAJ&amp;dq=%22fountain%20of%20indolence%22&amp;pg=PA144\">\"Exhibition of the Royal Academy\"</a>. <i>Arnold's Magazine of the Fine Arts</i>. New Series. <b>IV</b> (7): 144.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Arnold%27s+Magazine+of+the+Fine+Arts&amp;rft.atitle=Exhibition+of+the+Royal+Academy&amp;rft.volume=IV&amp;rft.issue=7&amp;rft.pages=144&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DGl0oAAAAYAAJ%26dq%3D%2522fountain%2520of%2520indolence%2522%26pg%3DPA144&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThe+Fountain+of+Indolence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Zalewski-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Zalewski_5-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Zalewski, Leanne (Summer 2012). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.19thc-artworldwide.org/summer12/leanne-zalewski-william-henry-vanderbilts-cultural-legacy\">\"Art for the public: William Henry Vanderbilt's cultural legacy\"</a>. <i>Nineteenth-Century Art Worldwide</i>. <b>11</b> (2)<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">4 February</span> 2014</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Nineteenth-Century+Art+Worldwide&amp;rft.atitle=Art+for+the+public%3A+William+Henry+Vanderbilt%27s+cultural+legacy&amp;rft.ssn=summer&amp;rft.volume=11&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft.date=2012&amp;rft.aulast=Zalewski&amp;rft.aufirst=Leanne&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.19thc-artworldwide.org%2Fsummer12%2Fleanne-zalewski-william-henry-vanderbilts-cultural-legacy&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThe+Fountain+of+Indolence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Poitras-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Poitras_6-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Poitras_6-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Poitras, Jacques (2007). <i>Beaverbrook: A Shattered Legacy</i>. Fredericton, New Brunswick: Goose Lane Editions. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780864925220\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9780864925220\">9780864925220</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Beaverbrook%3A+A+Shattered+Legacy&amp;rft.place=Fredericton%2C+New+Brunswick&amp;rft.pub=Goose+Lane+Editions&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft.isbn=9780864925220&amp;rft.aulast=Poitras&amp;rft.aufirst=Jacques&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThe+Fountain+of+Indolence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-CBC-7\"><span class=\"